segments.text: window washing, grounds keeping, et cetera.
And they've shown a tremendous commitment to even keep us, keep the planning program and the Institute of Urban Studies.
So it's both positive and negative.
It's been positive and negative for the last five years here.
And any of the negatives that I mentioned about planning at UT Arlington,
might be able to be viewed in that context.
From another perspective, we've accomplished a lot of interesting things in the planning program in the dozen years.
We've increased our enrollment steadily.
We're quite respectable in our numbers now.
as far as students go.
We've increased our visibility statewide in planning.
We are well looked upon, the planning program, in the Dallas-Fort Worth area from the governments.
Whenever I meet with the city, there's interest in what's going on.
The section's proud to have us here, APA Texas section.
And generally, we're well supported.
Our graduates have some interesting jobs.
One of them works for the city of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania housing agency.
Another one works as a regional planner for Lake Tahoe, Reno area.
One of them is planning director of Garland, Texas.
Another one's planning director of Mansfield.
They're out there.
One is with the consulting urban redevelopment firm.
And on and on.
They're very practical people.
They come out of here very practical and well thought of.
The materials have been good.
the university has supported us in computer hardware and software and in books and supplies.
There's been no lack of that.
I guess they took all our salary money and put it into that.
So I would say that there's
There has been a series of successes.
There has been a series of failures that have occurred.

And the biggest problem with planning at UT Arlington from an academic perspective is with four years in the School of Architecture under an architectural dean that had little understanding of planning,

two being moved after four years as a new program, to two years under the graduate dean who had no other academic programs under his tutelage on campus, and then to be moved to the Institute of Urban Studies.
To begin again, every time it set the planning program back as far as enrollments went, as far as developing went.
It was almost a new ballgame each time.
So in my opinion, the planning program at UT Arlington started three times.
Good point.
And there's a certain amount of just getting used to the new territory that the faculty would have to go through.
That is correct.
And of course, then you have the nuisance of changing your stationery all the time.
That's correct.
Which is the least of your problems, I'm sure.
And in a way, we've been moved now to an academic unit that is a troubled unit.
This academic unit is not within the budget of the university.
It's a line item of the governor's budget.
It's the Department of Urban Studies.
So we are funded as a separate tail item.
So at any time we are threatened,
in some budget-cutting legislative session.
We could be gone, so we live under the gun.
Yeah, you're very vulnerable.
Very vulnerable and not a pleasant position.
Whereas the other two places, we were financially safe and sound.
And that's just my opinion.
Do you think this will change?
It's very...
very much a concern to all the faculty in the Institute of Urban Studies what the legislature does every time it meets every two years.
Now there's a bill on the floor for them to meet every year, which would double your anxiety.
That's correct.
That's correct.
And then, of course, the institute, being a line item,
subject to a red pencil by the governor would include the planning program.
I believe so.
Well, I can only wish you well under those conditions.
Maybe what you need is a new dean like we're getting at Texas A&M who brings with him as part of his agreement to become dean a very strong financial commitment
from the institution.
He started out with $3.5 million for remodeling the building, which is only 10 years old, by the way.
And we will need to see just how much more he brings with him.
He accepted the position with the understanding that the administration intends it to be a first-rank college within the United States.
So we'll have to see what happens.
I frankly think he can do it, if he's given the resources that he's been promised.
I think he probably could.
I wish Arlington the same kind of good luck.
Any other points?
I think the city manager form of government is bad for Texas.
This may seem heresy.

The city manager form of government views planning as, in this metropolitan area, they view planning as subservient to their office of being coordinator and they frequently override planners' recommendations.
So as far as being an effective form of government to create urban change for the future, it doesn't.
It's reactive to business interests and resident interests.
So it becomes reactive as opposed to proactive.
Planning must be proactive.
There is an institutional conflict there between planning and city manager form of government.
You'd rather see a strong mayor type?
Yes, indeed.
Yes, indeed.

That's what El Paso has, and it has worked quite well there, because what that has done, in the case of John Cunningham, was to put him in the position of being a de facto city manager, as well as planning director.
Now, under I don't mean even...
And as to Valencia, we'll have to see what role planning has to play under a new personality.
Well, I think that the result of planning history, the result of any kind of planning history, is where is it now, where has it been in relation to that.
I think planning has had its difficulty in non-traditions due to the structure of government.
That an effective business manager, that is a city manager, is bottom line results dollar oriented.
Short term.
Which means short term.
Immediate.
Right.
And that is not long term.
And they run out of patience with
people who think in long range terms.
Because they have short term deadlines to make.
So planning in north central Texas, I think the great future is an environmental movement, environmental planning.
Because the pressure can be brought to bear to force planning to occur or people will die.
Or there'll be no place for the garbage.
Right.
Thank you very much, Joel.
I appreciate it.
Bye.
I guess that could work.
Just love your Lord.
